<DocPage eyebrow="UNITY / UI" title="Install and implement UI" lead="Add the UPM archive from the latest release. The runtime starts automatically and reflects runtime UI Toolkit, uGUI, and TextMeshPro controls." description="Install the Gua Unity package and reflect runtime UI." section="unity">
  <h2>1. Add the UPM package</h2><Callout kind="tip" title="Install from the latest release"><p>Open the <a href="https://github.com/link1345/gua/releases/latest">latest Gua release</a> and download <code>com.link1345.gua-&lt;version&gt;.tgz</code>. In Package Manager, choose <strong>Add package from tarball</strong> and select it. The released UPM archive is the normal installation path.</p></Callout><ol class="steps"><li><strong>Open the latest release</strong><p>Download the Unity <code>.tgz</code> from Assets.</p></li><li><strong>Add it in Package Manager</strong><p>Choose <strong>＋ → Add package from tarball</strong> and select the downloaded archive.</p></li><li><strong>Import the sample</strong><p>Open <strong>Samples</strong> on the Gua package page and import <strong>Runtime UI Fixture</strong> for a scene containing the supported UI systems.</p></li></ol>
  <Callout kind="warn" title="Player settings"><p>Use Windows x86_64, Mono, and the .NET Standard 2.1 API Compatibility Level. Import TMP Essential Resources before building when TextMeshPro is present.</p></Callout>
  <h2>2. Implement UI Toolkit controls</h2><p><code>BeforeSceneLoad</code> creates a hidden bootstrap driver and runtime. Users do not initialize, register semantic nodes, call frames, or dispose them manually. Place standard controls below a runtime <code>UIDocument</code>; <code>name</code> or <code>viewDataKey</code> provides stable identity.</p><CodeBlock title="Short UI Toolkit example" lang="csharp" code={`using UnityEngine;
using UnityEngine.UIElements;

public sealed class TitleScreen : MonoBehaviour
{
    [SerializeField] private UIDocument document;

    private void OnEnable()
    {
        var start = document.rootVisualElement.Q<Button>("start");
        start.clicked += () => Debug.Log("Start Game");
    }
}`} /><p>Set <code>name="start"</code> on the UXML Button. Buttons, toggles, text fields, sliders, dropdowns, and lists are reflected automatically.</p>
  <h2>3. Implement uGUI or TextMeshPro controls</h2><p>Place standard controls below a Canvas. Add <code>GuaId</code> when a GameObject needs a stable long-lived test ID.</p><CodeBlock title="Short uGUI example" lang="csharp" code={`using Gua.Unity;
using UnityEngine;
using UnityEngine.UI;

public sealed class TitleScreen : MonoBehaviour
{
    [SerializeField] private Button startButton;

    private void Awake()
    {
        var id = startButton.GetComponent<GuaId>()
            ?? startButton.gameObject.AddComponent<GuaId>();
        id.Value = "start";
        startButton.onClick.AddListener(() => Debug.Log("Start Game"));
    }
}`} /><p>TextMeshPro buttons, input fields, dropdowns, and text are collected from the same Canvas hierarchy. See <a href="https://github.com/link1345/gua/blob/47515fb/bindings/unity/Samples~/Runtime%20UI%20Fixture/GuaRuntimeUiSample.cs"><code>GuaRuntimeUiSample.cs</code></a> and <a href="https://github.com/link1345/gua/blob/47515fb/examples/unity-smoke/Assets/GuaUnityFixture.cs"><code>GuaUnityFixture.cs</code></a> for complete examples.</p>
  <h2>4. Add stable identity where needed</h2><p>UI Toolkit prefers <code>viewDataKey</code>, then <code>name</code>. uGUI/TMP prefers <code>GuaId.Value</code>, otherwise it derives an ID from scene path, Transform names, and sibling indices.</p>
  <CodeBlock title="Optional identity and screen" lang="csharp" code={`using Gua.Unity;
startButton.gameObject.AddComponent<GuaId>().Value = "start";
screenRoot.AddComponent<GuaScreen>().Value = "title";`} />
  <Callout kind="tip" title="ID contract"><p>Slashes are escaped as <code>~1</code>. IDs over 127 UTF-8 bytes are shortened with a hash suffix. For duplicates in one frame, the first node wins and later nodes are reported in runtime logs.</p></Callout>
  <Callout kind="warn" title="Use one GuaScreen"><p>If multiple <code>GuaScreen</code> components exist, the first one found wins, but discovery order is not a public contract. Keep one per logical screen.</p></Callout>
  <h2>5. Connect external tools</h2><p>The bridge listens on <code>8765</code> by default. Set <code>GUA_BRIDGE_PORT</code> before process startup to override it. Inspector and <code>gui-mcp</code> use the same bridge as other Gua adapters.</p>
  <h2>Observation rules</h2><ul><li>Hidden controls remain observable with <code>visible: false</code>; disabled state is reflected separately.</li><li>Bounds use physical screenshot pixels, top-left origin, X rightward, Y downward.</li><li>Actions are applied to Unity controls and completed with a request-correlated result.</li><li>Rendered Player and Play Mode support PNG capture. Batchmode or <code>-nographics</code> reports <code>headless</code>.</li></ul>
</DocPage>
